{"summary":"All three amendments are technically justified. One improves observability around a potentially lossy legacy-repair path, and the other two address real lineage-integrity defects in task-run matching and metadata updates.","votes":[{"amendment_id":"fr-11-9348c590","decision":"accept","rationale":"The fallback in the legacy completion-event repair path will overwrite malformed existing details whenever the raw string starts with 'project=', even after structured merge failed. That is intentionally permissive for recovery, but it is also potentially lossy. Emitting a warning when this branch fires is low-risk and materially improves auditability without changing normal behavior."},{"amendment_id":"fr-11-3f2dfcd6","decision":"accept","rationale":"This is a real correctness bug. `find_matching_running_task_run` will reuse a single runless open row for a requested run id even if another named open row for the same bead/project already exists, and `record_task_run_start` then backfills that row instead of rejecting the ambiguous state. The result is two simultaneous open attempts and corrupted lineage attribution. Rejecting the mixed-open case is the correct behavior and matches the stricter ambiguity handling already present in `update_task_run`."},{"amendment_id":"fr-11-84b6b1d6","decision":"accept","rationale":"The non-terminal-to-terminal update path silently drops a conflicting `plan_hash` once the running entry already has one, even though the terminal replay path explicitly treats `plan_hash` mismatches as conflicts. Returning success while ignoring conflicting caller metadata is inconsistent and undermines the audit value of the lineage record. The code should reject the mismatch or intentionally overwrite it, but not silently preserve stale data."}]}